ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
In this literature, we have successfully designed novel silver decorated nitrogen doped carbon dots/poly(3,4-ethylene-dioxythiophene):poly(styrenesulphonate)/poly (vinyl alcohol) (Ag@NCDots/PEDOT:PSS/PVA) nano-composite films for thermoelectric applications. The anisotropic (in plane//and through plane ⊥) thermoelectric functions are briefly studied, however we have focused on the through plane thermoelectric functions. It was found that both σ ⊥ and σ
// values increase with increasing the Ag@NCDots to be σ ⊥ = 181.7 ± 11 S/cm and σ
// = 287.4 ± 19 S/cm at 8 wt%, thanks to the creation of conductive paths inside the films and the increment in both carrier mobility and carrier concentration. Although k //~1.8k ⊥ was achieved at 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots, the films showed an under control behavior for k ⊥ with a value (0.195 W/mK) due to the creation of a gaseous atmosphere of nitrogen which occupies the defects and voids in the nano-composite. S //and S ⊥ values increase and the value of S ⊥ (77.5 ± 1.7 μV/K) has been achieved at 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots. The PF ⊥ ~109.20 ± 4 μV/mK2 and a ZT⊥ ~0.148 have been achieved at a minute concentration of Ag@NCDots (8 wt%) at room temperature. PF
// shows higher values than PF ⊥ because σ
// is higher than σ ⊥, while ZT // shows a smaller value than that in ZT⊥ at 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots as k ⊥ is lower than k
// . The films exhibited a much higher tensile strength (127.8 MPa) than PEDOT:PSS/PVA (42.2 MPa) and Young's modulus (1.52 GPa) larger than PEDOT:PSS/PVA (0.29 GPa) at the 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots, proving the excellent properties of this nano-composite for thermoelectric applications. 12 legs flexible thermoelectric generator has been engineered with an ability to generate an output voltage of (V
output = 15.12 mV) at a ΔT = 16 K. Finally, this nano-composite has a promising functional application as a flexible thermal sensor and wearable thermoelectric generators thanks to its unique properties and easy reproducibility.

ce:section.ce:para:
In fact, most literatures reported on studying the thermoelectric functions of the PEDOT:PSS polymeric materials are based on measuring the through plane k, in plane σ and in plane S for evaluating ZT of these materials which is considered a great issue due to the obtained ZT is called the apparent ZT
a and this doesn't represent the actual ZT values. Indeed, a preferred molecular orientation has been occurred for these polymer chains through fabricating their films, which could create anisotropic films. As a result, anisotropic thermoelectric functions are produced due to the creation of anisotropic films. So, it's extremely important to measure the in-plane k values as the σ and S values are measured in-plane in order to evaluate ZT values and vice versa. Toshima et al. [35] reported that, the in-plane k
// can be neglected when we deal with polymeric films with thick thickness. In fact, it is not easy to measure the precise in-plane k values for a thin film of a conducting polymer. Indeed, the difference in an in-plane and through-plane k values for the thick conducting polymer films is insignificant and very high for the thin films [35]. However, in this study we offer a full description of (in plane//and through plane ⊥) thermoelectric functions of Ag@NCDots/PPVA films.

The anisotropic thermoelectric performances of Ag@NCDots/PPVA were briefly studied, and it was found to be adjusted by the concentration of Ag@NCDots nanoparticles. The in plane σ

                        //
                     and through plane σ
                     ⊥ values were increased with increasing the Ag@NCDots and it was found to be σ

                        //
                     = 287.4 ± 19 S/cm thanks to the nano-crystals of PEDOT are well-packed in the films and σ
                     ⊥ = 181.7 ± 11 S/cm at (8 wt% of Ag@NCDots) due to the creation of conductive paths inside the films and the increase in carrier mobility and carrier concentration. Also, Ag@NCDots/PPVA nano-composite showed an under control behavior of k
                     ⊥ with value (0.195 ± 0.007 W/mK) thanks to the formation of a gaseous atmosphere of nitrogen which fill the defects and voids in the films. The k

                        //
                     is higher than k
                     ⊥ (k
                     //~1.8k
                     ⊥ at 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots) due to the orientation alignment of PSS chains in the film. In fact, both the S
                        //
                     and S⊥ are increased with the growth of Ag@NCDots concentration, however, the S
                     ⊥ (77.5 ± 1.7 μV/K) was obtained at the 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots. In addition, the PF
                     ⊥ was 109.0 ± 4 μV/mK2 and a ZT
                     ⊥ ~0.148 ± 0.008 at 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots nanoparticles at room temperature. The in plane PF

                        //
                     showed higher values than the PF
                     ⊥ due to the σ

                        //
                     higher than σ
                     ⊥, while the ZT

                        //
                     showed a lower value than that ZT
                     ⊥ at 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots due to the k
                     ⊥ is lower than k

                        //
                     at the same concentration. However, the nanocomposite exhibited a high ZT value either in plane or through plane, which give these materials the opportunity to be good thermoelectrics. Also, Ag@NCDots/PPVA films displayed a much higher tensile strength (127.8 MPa) than PEDOT:PSS/PVA (42.2 MPa) and Young's modulus (1.52 MPa) larger than PEDOT:PSS/PVA (0.29 MPa) at the 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots nano-particles, proving the excellent properties of this nano-composite for thermoelectric applications. Also, a flexible generator with 12 legs has been engineered and it was found that the generator produces output voltage (15.12 mV) and ΔT = 16 K. It is expected that Ag@NCDots/PPVA system may discover prospective applications in the engineering of many industries such as thermal sensors and flexible/wearable thermoelectric power generation devices.

The films were cut into strips and coated with Ag paste in order to measure the through plane S
                        ⊥ values of Ag@NCDots/PPVA films. The measuring uncertainty of S
                        ⊥ was ≥5%. The in plane S

                           //
                        values were measured by four probe method, Supporting Information S4. The measuring uncertainty of S

                           //
                        was ≥5%. Nanovoltmeter (Keithley 616) was applied to detect the output voltage, which is thermally generated between the two ends of the strip. The out of plane (Through plane) thermal conductivities k
                        ⊥ of Ag@NCDots/PPVA films were measured by steady state home-made device, for more details see our previous work [4]. The measuring uncertainty of k
                        ⊥ was > 10%. The in plane thermal conductivity k

                           //
                        values are measured by 3-ω method. The measuring uncertainty of k

                           //
                        was > 8%. The combined uncertainty for all measurements participated in the calculation of ZT is > 20%. For five different samples, the error bars are evaluated for calculating the standard derivation by taking into account the equipment uncertainties. All measurements of the thermoelectric parameters of Ag@NCDots/PPVA films were done at room temperature. More details about the measurements are presented and shown in section Supporting Information S5,S6. The thermoelectric generator is engineered by cutting the films into legs with (20 × 2 mm) in dimensions and placed on a PET film with a distance = 10 mm between each two legs. By using silver paste and silver wires, the legs were connected to get a good electrical contact. By using a Keithley apparatus, the output power (Poutput) of the generator is measured.

Fig. 8
