⊥ increased with the Ag@NCDots. A similar behavior has been observed in Ref. [45]. As detected, the S
//is 35.86 ± 4 μV/K for PPVA. Also, the S
//increased to be 50.31 ± 4, 56.73 ± 3, 60.47 ± 3 and 65.55 ± 3 μV/K for 2, 4, 6 and 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots. Alternatively, the S
⊥ of PVVA is 17.26 ± 2 μV/K. The S
⊥ values increased to be 45.26 ± 2, 54.53 ± 3, 68.07 ± 3 and 77.53 ± 2 μV/K for 2, 4, 6 and 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots. In fact, the obtained S
⊥ (77.53 ± 2 μV/K) and S//(65.55 ± 3 μV/K) values for our material are larger than that of S//of the previously reported research such as graphene/PEDOT:PSS (22.5 μV/K) [65], 4 wt% MoS2/PEDOT:PSS (19.5 μV/K) [66], and 29.6 wt% Ge/EDOT:PSS (58.9 μV/K) [68] however, they are still lower than that of Te NWs/PEDOT:PSS (114.9 μV/K) [67].

On the other hand, Fig. 9 shows both PF ⊥ and PF
// values of the said films increased with the growth in the Ag@NCDots concentration. As seen, the PF
// is 32.06 ± 5 μW/mK2 for PPVA and this value increased to be 65.40 ± 6, 86.22 ± 5, 100.74 ± 7 and 123.54 ± 6 μW/mK2 for 2, 4, 6 and 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots. Alternatively, the PF ⊥ is 0.68 ± 0.2 μW/mK2 for PPVA and this value increased to be 11.45 ± 2, 31.02 ± 4, 54.15 ± 2 and 109.22 ± 4 μW/mK2 for 2, 4, 6 and 8 wt% of Ag@NCDots.

